{"title_page": "Ian Mellor", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n'''Ian Mellor''' (born 19 February 1950) is an English former professional [[association football|footballer]]. He was born in [[Sale, Greater Manchester|Sale]], England.\n\nMellor, a [[Midfielder#Winger|left-winger]], began his career with [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]. He played as a substitute as City won the [[1972 FA Charity Shield]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/CommunityShield/1972-73CharityShield.htm |title=1972/73 Charity Shield |website=footballsite.co.uk |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> He then moved to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] in 1973 for a fee of \u00a365,000. The Canaries were struggling against relegation in their first season in English football's top division when Mellor joined. He played in the last eleven league games of the season and played his part in helping the club stay up. He went on to score nine goals in 43 games for Norwich before playing for [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton]] where he was known as \"Spider\". and then in February 1978 moving for \u00a325,000 to [[Chester City F.C.|Chester]],<ref>{{cite book | author=Chas Sumner | title=On the Borderline: The Official History of Chester City 1885-1997 | year=1997| pages= 93|isbn=1-874427-52-6}}</ref> He helped Chester finish fifth in [[Division Three]] in his first season and was on target in a [[Football League Cup]] giantkilling against [[Football League First Division|First Division]] side [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] early in [[1978-79 in English football|1978\u201379]].\n\nAt the end of the season Mellor moved to [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]],securing a place in Wednesday history by scoring in the 4\u20130 defeat of Sheffield United, in the famous 'Boxing Day Massacre', here he remained until joining [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] in June 1982. He also played briefly in Hong Kong for Tung Sing. He spent two seasons with City before ending his professional career.\n\nMellor is the father of former [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] striker [[Neil Mellor]].\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|title=Canary Citizens|author=Mike Davage, John Eastwood, Kevin Platt|publisher=Jarrold Publishing|year=2001|isbn=0-7117-2020-7}}\n*[http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player1/ianmellor.html Ian Mellor], Post War English & Scottish Football League A - Z Player's Transfer Database\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mellor, Ian}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:People from Sale, Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Norwich City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Kiveton Park F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield Wednesday F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n\n\n{{england-footy-midfielder-1950s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n'''Ian Mellor''' (born 19 February 1950) is an English former professional [[association football|footballer]]. He was born in [[Sale, Greater Manchester|Sale]], England.\n\nMellor, a [[Midfielder#Winger|left-winger]], began his career with [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]. He played as a substitute as City won the [[1972 FA Charity Shield]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/CommunityShield/1972-73CharityShield.htm |title=1972/73 Charity Shield |website=footballsite.co.uk |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> He then moved to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] in 1973 for a fee of \u00a365,000. The Canaries were struggling against relegation in their first season in English football's top division when Mellor joined. He played in the last eleven league games of the season and played his part in helping the club stay up. He went on to score nine goals in 43 games for Norwich before playing for [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton]] where he was known as \"Spider\". and then in February 1978 moving for \u00a325,000 to [[Chester City F.C.|Chester]],<ref>{{cite book | author=Chas Sumner | title=On the Borderline: The Official History of Chester City 1885-1997 | year=1997| pages= 93|isbn=1-874427-52-6}}</ref> He helped Chester finish fifth in [[Division Three]] in his first season and was on target in a [[Football League Cup]] giantkilling against [[Football League First Division|First Division]] side [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] early in [[1978-79 in English football|1978\u201379]].\n\nAt the end of the season Mellor moved to [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]],securing a place in Wednesday history by scoring in the 4\u20130 defeat of Sheffield United, in the famous 'Boxing Day Massacre', here he remained until joining [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] in June 1982. He also played briefly in Hong Kong for Tung Sing.  He spent two seasons with City before ending his professional career.\n\nMellor is the father of former [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] striker [[Neil Mellor]].\n\n==References==\n*''Canary Citizens'' by Mike Davage, John Eastwood, Kevin Platt, published by Jarrold Publishing, (2001), {{ISBN|0-7117-2020-7}}\n*[http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player1/ianmellor.html Ian Mellor], Post War English & Scottish Football League A - Z Player's Transfer Database\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mellor, Ian}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:People from Sale, Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Norwich City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Kiveton Park F.C. players]]\n[[