e_user": "Bobly", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eQuarterfinals", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1987%E2%80%9388_Real_Madrid_CF_season"}
{"title_page": "Ian McCall (footballer)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name      = Ian McCall\n| image = Ian McCall (football manager).jpg\n| image_size = 250\n| alt =\n| caption =\n| fullname = Ian Holland McCall<ref>{{Hugman|12217|accessdate=16 March 2017}}</ref>\n| height = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1964|9|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Dumfries]], Scotland\n| currentclub = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] (manager)\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| years1  = 1983\u20131986 \n| years2  = 1986\u20131987 \n| years3  = 1987\u20131989 \n| years4  = 1989\u20131990 \n| years5  = 1990\u20131991 \n| years6  = 1991\u20131992 \n| years7  = 1992\u20131994 \n| years8  = 1994\u20131995 \n| years9  = 1995\u20131996 \n| years10 = 1996\u20131997 \n| years11 = 1997\u20131998\n| clubs1  = [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] \n| clubs2  = [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]] \n| clubs3  = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] \n| clubs4  = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] \n| clubs5  = [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]] \n| clubs6  = [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]] \n| clubs7  = [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] \n| clubs8  = [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]] \n| clubs9  = [[Happy Valley Athletic Association|Happy Valley]] \n| clubs10 = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] \n| clubs11 = [[Clydebank F.C.|Clydebank]] \n| caps1   = 66   \n| caps2   = 47   \n| caps3   = 21   \n| caps4   = 12   \n| caps5   = 38   \n| caps6   = 27   \n| caps7   = 75   \n| caps8   = 6   \n| caps9   =   \n| caps10  = 7   \n| caps11  = 21   \n| totalcaps = 320 \n| goals1  = 9  \n| goals2  = 8  \n| goals3  = 2  \n| goals4  = 1  \n| goals5  = 5  \n| goals6  = 9  \n| goals7  = 9  \n| goals8  = 1  \n| goals9   =\n| goals10  = 0  \n| goals11  = 1  \n| totalgoals  = 45\n| manageryears1 = 1997\u20132000 \n| manageryears2 = 2000 \n| manageryears3 = 2001\u20132002 \n| manageryears4 = 2002\u20132003 \n| manageryears5 = 2003\u20132005 \n| manageryears6 = 2005\u20132007 \n| manageryears7 = 2007\u20132011\n| manageryears8 = 2015\u20132019\n| manageryears9 = 2019\u2013\n| managerclubs1 = [[Clydebank F.C.|Clydebank]] \n| managerclubs2 = [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]] \n| managerclubs3 = [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrieonians]] \n| managerclubs4 = [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] \n| managerclubs5 = [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] \n| managerclubs6 = [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] \n| managerclubs7 = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]\n| managerclubs8 = [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]]\n| managerclubs9 = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]\n}}\n'''Ian Holland McCall''' (born 30 September 1964) is a Scottish former [[association football|football]] player and coach, who is currently the manager of [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]. During his playing days McCall played for [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]], [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]], [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]], [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]], [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]], [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]], [[Happy Valley Athletic Association|Happy Valley]], [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] and [[Clydebank F.C.|Clydebank]].\n\nHe then began an extensive managerial career, mostly in the lower leagues of Scotland starting with  Clydebank, [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]], [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrieonians]], [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]], [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]], Partick Thistle and  [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]].\n\n==Playing career==\nIan McCall was born in [[Dumfries]], Scotland. In his boyhood, he was a regular on the Palmerston terraces watching [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]]. His hopes of playing for his home town club were dashed, though, by then chairman Willie Harkness. \"I played a trial game for the club, and thought I did reasonably well,\" McCall recalls. \"[[Drew Busby]] was the manager, but I was told by Willie Harkness I might not make the grade. Instead I went to [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]], and then three years after that was sold to Rangers for \u00a3250,000.\"<ref name=\"sunher\">[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4156/is_20070218/ai_n18625522/ \"DOWN HOME BOY For a man of only 41 he may have been round the block\" \u2013 ''Sunday Herald'', 18 February 2007]</ref>\n\nMcCall began his career as a midfielder for Queen's Park in 1983, then was with [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]] from 1986 to 1987, and [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] from 1987 to 1990. He was transferred to [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] for \u00a3200,000 before rejoining Dunfermline. His playing career also included spells with [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]], [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]], [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]], [[Happy Valley Athletic Association|Happy Valley]] in Hong Kong and [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] back in Scotland. His final club as a player was [[Clydebank F.C.|Clydebank]], where he became player-manager during the [[1997\u201398 in Scottish football|1997\u201398 season]].\n\nMcCall never made more than 75 league appearances in a single spell for one club. He made 85 league appearances for Dunfermline broken over two separate periods with the Fife club.\n\n==Managerial career==\nHis spell at Clydebank took place against the backdrop of an abortive scheme to relocate the club to [[Dublin]].\n\nIn 17 games in charge at [[Morton F.C.|Morton]], McCall achieved five wins and 9 defeats.\n\nThis was followed by a move to [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrieonians]]. Airdrie challenged for promotion to the [[Scottish Premier League]] before the club's extinction in 2002, making McCall the last manager in the club's history. McCall won 23 of his 65 games in charge.\n\nA spell, at Falkirk,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://falkirkfchistorian.blogspot.com/p/falkirk-fc-managers.html|title=Falkirk Football Historian: Falkirk FC Managers|publisher=}}</ref> with the best win rate of his managerial career, led to McCall twice being offered the manager's job at [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], which he finally accepted in January 2003. In McCall's first top flight managerial season the Tayside Club achieved a top-6 finish, but in the following season with the club in a relegation battle he was sacked in March 2005.\n\nIn November 2005, Ian McCall returned to management with his home town club Queen of the South. After a less than auspicious start to his reign as Queen of the South manager, the Palmerston outfit enjoyed somewhat of a resurgence in the early months of 2006, finally securing eight position in the league and thus avoiding having to play-off to maintain first division status. 2006/07 provided a second relegation battle. [[Allan Jenkins (footballer)|Allan Jenkins]] scored the Stranraer winner on a 2 January South West relegation derby leaving Queens firmly in the play off spot that was ninth place.<ref name=\"str\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stranraer-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadtmrs.asp?ssnno=135&teamno=503 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-09-27 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120918094511/http://www.stranraer-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadtmrs.asp?ssnno=135&teamno=503 |archive-date=18 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }} \"Stranraer results 2005/2006\"</ref> However Jenkins was sold to Gretna 10 days later.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=15145] Allan Jenkins at Soccerbase</ref> Stranraer's league form imploded immediately recording only one other league win from then until the season's end.<ref name = \"str\"/> Despite narrowly avoiding relegation, Ian McCall was sacked by Queen of the South, with his assistant [[Gordon Chisholm]] taking over. His departure from Queen of the South was in bitter circumstances. McCall fielded an ineligible player in [[Jamie Adams]] in a Scottish Cup run early in 2007. Queens were fined \u00a320,000 by the SFA. Chairman [[Davie Rae]] described the fine as, \"A considerable sum\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.scotsman.com/queenofthesouthfc/Queens-hit-by-20000-fine.3288272.jp|title=Queens hit by \u00a320,000 fine|publisher=}}</ref> McCall's departure from Queens was at the season's end.<ref name=autogenerateddg>{{cite web |url=http://icdumfries.icnetwork.co.uk/gallowaynews/sport/tm_headline=mccall-grasps-the-thistle&method=full&objectid=19225906&siteid=77296-name_page.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100518112837/http://icdumfries.icnetwork.co.uk/gallowaynews/sport/tm_headline%3Dmccall-grasps-the-thistle%26method%3Dfull%26objectid%3D19225906%26siteid%3D77296-name_page.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 May 2010 |title=Glasgow - Daily Record |publisher= |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 70 games in charge McCall notched 19 wins.\n\nHe became manager of [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] in May 2007.<ref name=autogenerateddg /> staying until 15 April 2011 when he departed after achieving 70 wins from 179 games in charge. In his first season in charge, McCall largely rebuilt the squad, bringing in players such as Marc Twaddle, Gary Harkins and Liam Buchanan, each of whom would go on to serve with distinction at the club.\n\nAfter three years out of the game, McCall was appointed manager of [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]] in January 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/305477-ian-mccall-named-new-manager-of-struggling-league-1-side-ayr-united/ |title=Ian McCall named new manager of struggling League 1 side Ayr United |work=STV Sport |publisher=STV |date=5 January 2015 |accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref> He led the \"Honest Men\" to promotion to the [[Scottish Championship]] through the play-offs in [[2015-16 in Scottish football|May 2016]]. They were relegated the following season in [[2016-17 in Scottish football|May 2017]]. McCall then led an instant promotion back to the second tier in [[2017-18 in Scottish football|the following season]] by winning the [[Scottish League One]] title. Ayr reached the promotion playoffs in 2018\u201319. McCall left the club in September 2019 to join Partick Thistle.<ref name = mccall>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49798938 |title=Partick Thistle: Ian McCall appointed manager after Ayr United exit |website=BBC Sport |date=23 September 2019 |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Media work==\n\nMcCall has worked for a number of years as a media pundit. McCall commented, \"I can't really slag my bosses at the BBC because they're my pals.\"<ref name = \"sunher\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMcCall lives in Glasgow. He has a son, called Edson from a previous marriage.<ref>http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/providing-the-home-support-1-546565</ref><ref>http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/partick-thistle-boss-ian-mccall-1009168</ref>\n\n==Honours and Achievements==\n\n===Player===\n;Falkirk\n*[[Scottish Challenge Cup]] (1): [[1992-93 in Scottish football|1992-93]]\n\n===Manager===\n;Clydebank\n*[[Scottish Football League Second Division|Scottish Second Division]] promotion: [[1997-98 in Scottish football|1997-98]]\n\n;Airdrieonians\n*[[Scottish Challenge Cup]] : [[2001-02 in Scottish football|2001-02]]\n\n;Falkirk\n*[[Stirlingshire Cup]]: 2002-03\n\n;Dundee United\n*[[Forfarshire Cup]]: 2004-05\n\n;Ayr United\n*[[Scottish Championship]] play-offs: [[2015-16 in Scottish football|2015-16]]\n*[[Scottish League One]] : [[2017-18 in Scottish football|2017-18]]\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|match played 10 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=\"5\"|Record\n|-\n!G!!W!!D!!L!!Win %\n|-\n|align=left|[[Clydebank F.C.|Clydebank]]\n|align=left|1996\n|align=left|2000\n{{WDL|113|36|31|46}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]]\n|align=left|2000\n|align=left|2000\n{{WDL|17|5|3|9}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrieonians]]\n|align=left|2001\n|align=left|2002\n{{WDL|65|23|25|17}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]\n|align=left|2002\n|align=left|2003\n{{WDL|30|18|9|3}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]\n|align=left|2003\n|align=left|2005\n{{WDL|92|28|24|40}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]]\n|align=left|2005\n|align=left|2007\n{{WDL|70|19|24|27}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]\n|align=left|2007\n|align=left|2011\n{{WDL|179|70|46|63}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]]\n|align=left|2015\n|align=left|2019\n{{WDL|217|100|44|73}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]\n|align=left|2019\n|align=left|''Present''\n{{WDL|27|9|6|12}}\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n{{WDLtot|697|272|181|244}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{soccerbase (manager)|1614|Ian McCall}}\n*{{NeilBrownPlayers|player/ianmccall}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Ian McCall managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{Clydebank F.C. managers}}\n{{Greenock Morton F.C. managers}}\n{{Airdrieonians F.C. (1878) managers}}\n{{Falkirk F.C. managers}}  \n{{Dundee United F.C. managers}}\n{{Queen of the South F.C. managers}}\n{{Partick Thistle F.C. managers}}\n{{Ayr United F.C. managers}}\n}}\n{{Partick Thistle F.C. squad}}\n{{SPFL managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCall, Ian}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish football managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Dunfermline Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Greenock Morton F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Dundee F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hamilton Academical F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate sportspeople in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Falkirk F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Partick Thistle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Happy Valley AA players]]\n[[Category:Clydebank F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Greenock Morton F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Airdrieonians F.C. (1878) managers]]\n[[Category:Falkirk F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Dundee United F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Queen of the South F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Partick Thistle F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong First Division League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Dumfries]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League managers]]\n[[Category:Ayr United F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League managers]]\n[[Category:Clydebank F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Queen's Park F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name      = Ian McCall\n| image = File:Ian McCall (football manager).jpg\n| image_size = 300px\n| alt =\n| caption =\n| fullname = Ian Holland McCall<ref>{{Hugman|12217|accessdate=16 March 2017}}</ref>\n| height = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1964|9|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Dumfries]], Scotland\n| currentclub = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] (manager)\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| years1  = 1983\u20131986 \n| years2  = 1986\u20131987 \n| years3  = 1987\u20131989 \n| years4  = 1989\u20131990 \n| years5  = 1990\u20131991 \n| years6  = 1991\u20131992 \n| years7  = 1992\u20131994 \n| years8  = 1994\u20131995 \n| years9  = 1995\u20131996 \n| years10 = 1996\u20131997 \n| years11 = 1997\u20131998\n| clubs1  = [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] \n| clubs2  = [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]] \n| clubs3  = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] \n| clubs4  = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] \n| clubs5  = [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]] \n| clubs6  = [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]] \n| clubs7  = [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] \n| clubs8  = [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]] \n| clubs9  = [[Happy Valley Athletic Association|Happy Valley]] \n| clubs10 = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] \n| clubs11 = [[Clydebank F.C.|Clydebank]] \n| caps1   = 66   \n| caps2   = 47   \n| caps3   = 21   \n| caps4   = 12   \n| caps5   = 38   \n| caps6   = 27   \n| caps7   = 75   \n| caps8   = 6   \n| caps9   =   \n| caps10  = 7   \n| caps11  = 21   \n| totalcaps = 320 \n| goals1  = 9  \n| goals2  = 8  \n| goals3  = 2  \n| goals4  = 1  \n| goals5  = 5  \n| goals6  = 9  \n| goals7  = 9  \n| goals8  = 1  \n| goals9   =\n| goals10  = 0  \n| goals11  = 1  \n| totalgoals  = 45\n| manageryears1 = 1997\u20132000 \n| manageryears2 = 2000 \n| manageryears3 = 2001\u20132002 \n| manageryears4 = 2002\u20132003 \n| manageryears5 = 2003\u20132005 \n| manageryears6 = 2005\u20132007 \n| manageryears7 = 2007\u20132011\n| manageryears8 = 2015\u20132019\n| manageryears9 = 2019\u2013\n| managerclubs1 = [[Clydebank F.C.|Clydebank]] \n| managerclubs2 = [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]] \n| managerclubs3 = [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrieonians]] \n| managerclubs4 = [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] \n| managerclubs5 = [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] \n| managerclubs6 = [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] \n| managerclubs7 = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]\n| managerclubs8 = [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]]\n| managerclubs9 = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]\n}}\n'''Ian Holland McCall''' (born 30 September 1964) is a Scottish former [[association football|football]] player and coach, who is currently the manager of [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]. During his playing days McCall played for [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]], [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]], [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]], [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]], [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]], [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]], [[Happy Valley Athletic Association|Happy Valley]], [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] and [[Clydebank F.C.|Clydebank]].\n\nHe then began an extensive managerial career, mostly in the lower leagues of Scotland starting with  Clydebank, [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]], [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrieonians]], [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]], [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]], Partick Thistle and  [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]].\n\n==Playing career==\nIan McCall was born in [[Dumfries]], Scotland. In his boyhood, he was a regular on the Palmerston terraces watching [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]]. His hopes of playing for his home town club were dashed, though, by then chairman Willie Harkness. \"I played a trial game for the club, and thought I did reasonably well,\" McCall recalls. \"[[Drew Busby]] was the manager, but I was told by Willie Harkness I might not make the grade. Instead I went to [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]], and then three years after that was sold to Rangers for \u00a3250,000.\"<ref name=\"sunher\">[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4156/is_20070218/ai_n18625522/ \"DOWN HOME BOY For a man of only 41 he may have been round the block\" \u2013 ''Sunday Herald'', 18 February 2007]</ref>\n\nMcCall began his career as a midfielder for Queen's Park in 1983, then was with [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]] from 1986 to 1987, and [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] from 1987 to 1990. He was transferred to [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] for \u00a3200,000 before rejoining Dunfermline. His playing career also included spells with [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]], [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]], [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]], [[Happy Valley Athletic Association|Happy Valley]] in Hong Kong and [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] back in Scotland. His final club as a player was [[Clydebank F.C.|Clydebank]], where he became player-manager during the [[1997\u201398 in Scottish football|1997\u201398 season]].\n\nMcCall never made more than 75 league appearances in a single spell for one club. He made 85 league appearances for Dunfermline broken over two separate periods with the Fife club.\n\n==Managerial career==\nHis spell at Clydebank took place against the backdrop of an abortive scheme to relocate the club to [[Dublin]].\n\nIn 17 games in charge at [[Morton F.C.|Morton]], McCall achieved five wins and 9 defeats.\n\nThis was followed by a move to [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrieonians]]. Airdrie challenged for promotion to the [[Scottish Premier League]] before the club's extinction in 2002, making McCall the last manager in the club's history. McCall won 23 of his 65 games in charge.\n\nA spell, at Falkirk,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://falkirkfchistorian.blogspot.com/p/falkirk-fc-managers.html|title=Falkirk Football Historian: Falkirk FC Managers|publisher=}}</ref> with the best win rate of his managerial career, led to McCall twice being offered the manager's job at [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], which he finally accepted in January 2003. In McCall's first top flight managerial season the Tayside Club achieved a top-6 finish, but in the following season with the club in a relegation battle he was sacked in March 2005.\n\nIn November 2005, Ian McCall returned to management with his home town club Queen of the South. After a less than auspicious start to his reign as Queen of the South manager, the Palmerston outfit enjoyed somewhat of a resurgence in the early months of 2006, finally securing eight position in the league and thus avoiding having to play-off to maintain first division status. 2006/07 provided a second relegation battle. [[Allan Jenkins (footballer)|Allan Jenkins]] scored the Stranraer winner on a 2 January South West relegation derby leaving Queens firmly in the play off spot that was ninth place.<ref name=\"str\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stranraer-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadtmrs.asp?ssnno=135&teamno=503 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-09-27 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120918094511/http://www.stranraer-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadtmrs.asp?ssnno=135&teamno=503 |archive-date=18 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }} \"Stranraer results 2005/2006\"</ref> However Jenkins was sold to Gretna 10 days later.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=15145] Allan Jenkins at Soccerbase</ref> Stranraer's league form imploded immediately recording only one other league win from then until the season's end.<ref name = \"str\"/> Despite narrowly avoiding relegation, Ian McCall was sacked by Queen of the South, with his assistant [[Gordon Chisholm]] taking over. His departure from Queen of the South was in bitter circumstances. McCall fielded an ineligible player in [[Jamie Adams]] in a Scottish Cup run early in 2007. Queens were fined \u00a320,000 by the SFA. Chairman [[Davie Rae]] described the fine as, \"A considerable sum\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.scotsman.com/queenofthesouthfc/Queens-hit-by-20000-fine.3288272.jp|title=Queens hit by \u00a320,000 fine|publisher=}}</ref> McCall's departure from Queens was at the season's end.<ref name=autogenerateddg>{{cite web |url=http://icdumfries.icnetwork.co.uk/gallowaynews/sport/tm_headline=mccall-grasps-the-thistle&method=full&objectid=19225906&siteid=77296-name_page.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100518112837/http://icdumfries.icnetwork.co.uk/gallowaynews/sport/tm_headline%3Dmccall-grasps-the-thistle%26method%3Dfull%26objectid%3D19225906%26siteid%3D77296-name_page.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 May 2010 |title=Glasgow - Daily Record |publisher= |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 70 games in charge McCall notched 19 wins.\n\nHe became manager of [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] in May 2007.<ref name=autogenerateddg /> staying until 15 April 2011 when he departed after achieving 70 wins from 179 games in charge. In his first season in charge, McCall largely rebuilt the squad, bringing in players such as Marc Twaddle, Gary Harkins and Liam Buchanan, each of whom would go on to serve with distinction at the club.\n\nAfter three years out of the game, McCall was appointed manager of [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]] in January 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/305477-ian-mccall-named-new-manager-of-struggling-league-1-side-ayr-united/ |title=Ian McCall named new manager of struggling League 1 side Ayr United |work=STV Sport |publisher=STV |date=5 January 2015 |accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref> He led the \"Honest Men\" to promotion to the [[Scottish Championship]] through the play-offs in [[2015-16 in Scottish football|May 2016]]. They were relegated the following season in [[2016-17 in Scottish football|May 2017]]. McCall then led an instant promotion back to the second tier in [[2017-18 in Scottish football|the following season]] by winning the [[Scottish League One]] title. Ayr reached the promotion playoffs in 2018&ndash;19. McCall left the club in September 2019 to join Partick Thistle.<ref name = mccall>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49798938 |title=Partick Thistle: Ian McCall appointed manager after Ayr United exit |website=BBC Sport |date=23 September 2019 |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Media work==\n\nMcCall has worked for a number of years as a media pundit. McCall commented, \"I can't really slag my bosses at the BBC because they're my pals.\"<ref name = \"sunher\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMcCall lives in Glasgow. He has a son, called Edson from a previous marriage.<ref>http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/providing-the-home-support-1-546565</ref><ref>http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/partick-thistle-boss-ian-mccall-1009168</ref>\n\n==Honours and Achievements==\n\n===Player===\n;Falkirk\n*[[Scottish Challenge Cup]] (1): [[1992-93 in Scottish football|1992-93]]\n\n===Manager===\n;Clydebank\n*[[Scottish Football League Second Division|Scottish Second Division]] promotion: [[1997-98 in Scottish football|1997-98]]\n\n;Airdrieonians\n*[[Scottish Challenge Cup]] : [[2001-02 in Scottish football|2001-02]]\n\n;Falkirk\n*[[Stirlingshire Cup]]: 2002-03\n\n;Dundee United\n*[[Forfarshire Cup]]: 2004-05\n\n;Ayr United\n*[[Scottish Championship]] play-offs: [[2015-16 in Scottish football|2015-16]]\n*[[Scottish League One]] : [[2017-18 in Scottish football|2017-18]]\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|match played 10 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=\"5\"|Record\n|-\n!G!!W!!D!!L!!Win %\n|-\n|align=left|[[Clydebank F.C.|Clydebank]]\n|align=left|1996\n|align=left|2000\n{{WDL|113|36|31|46}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]]\n|align=left|2000\n|align=left|2000\n{{WDL|17|5|3|9}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrieonians]]\n|align=left|2001\n|align=left|2002\n{{WDL|65|23|25|17}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]\n|align=left|2002\n|align=left|2003\n{{WDL|30|18|9|3}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]\n|align=left|2003\n|align=left|2005\n{{WDL|92|28|24|40}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]]\n|align=left|2005\n|align=left|2007\n{{WDL|70|19|24|27}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]\n|align=left|2007\n|align=left|2011\n{{WDL|179|70|46|63}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]]\n|align=left|2015\n|align=left|2019\n{{WDL|217|100|44|73}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]\n|align=left|2019\n|align=left|''Present''\n{{WDL|27|9|6|12}}\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n{{WDLtot|697|272|181|244}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{soccerbase (manager)|1614|Ian McCall}}\n*{{NeilBrownPlayers|player/ianmccall}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Ian McCall managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{Clydebank F.C. managers}}\n{{Greenock Morton F.C. managers}}\n{{Airdrieonians F.C. (1878) managers}}\n{{Falkirk F.C. managers}}  \n{{Dundee United F.C. managers}}\n{{Queen of the South F.C. managers}}\n{{Partick Thistle F.C. managers}}\n{{Ayr United F.C. managers}}\n}}\n{{Partick Thistle F.C. squad}}\n{{SPFL managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCall, Ian}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish football managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Dunfermline Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Greenock Morton F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Dundee F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hamilton Academical F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate sportspeople in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Falkirk F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Partick Thistle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Happy Valley AA players]]\n[[Category:Clydebank F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Greenock Morton F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Airdrieonians F.C. (1878) managers]]\n[[Category:Falkirk F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Dundee United F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Queen of the South F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Partick Thistle F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong First Division League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Dumfries]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League managers]]\n[[Category:Ayr United F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League managers]]\n[[Category:Clydebank F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Queen's Park F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ian_McCall_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Christopher Andersen", "text_new": "{{about||the american baseballer Andersen|people of a similar name|Christopher Anderson (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|name=boris Johnson \n|birth_name=Christopher Peter Andersen\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1949|5|26}}\n|birth_place=[[Philippines]]\n|death_date=2004\n|death_place=west minister abbey \n|occupation=[[Journalist]], [[author]]\n|language=[[English language|English]]\n|genre=[[Journalism]], [[biography]]\n}}\n\n'''Christopher Peter Andersen''' (born May 26, 1949) is an [[United States|American]] [[journalist]] and the author of 34 books, including many bestsellers.\n\n==Life==\nA graduate of the [[University of California at Berkeley]], Andersen joined the staff of ''[[Time Magazine]]'' as a contributing editor in 1969.<ref>{{cite news | title=Search Results for Christopher Andersen | url=http://search.time.com/results.html?N=0&Nty=1&Ntt=Christopher+Andersen&x=17&y=18&p=0&cmd=tags&srchCat=Full+Archive | work=Time | date=June 6, 2007 | access-date=February 14, 2010 | archive-url=https://archive.is/20120718134611/http://search.time.com/results.html?N=0&Nty=1&Ntt=Christopher+Andersen&x=17&y=18&p=0&cmd=tags&srchCat=Full+Archive | archive-date=July 18, 2012 |url-status = dead| df=mdy-all }}</ref>  From 1974 to 1986 Andersen was senior editor of Time Incorporated's ''[[People Magazine]]''.<ref>[http://search.people.com/TIISearch/people/search/search.html?search=Christopher+Andersen&bu=&searchSubmit.x=19&searchSubmit.y=17 People.com] {{dead link|date=September 2018}}</ref>  He has also written for a wide range of  publications, including ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''The New York Daily News'',<ref>{{cite news | title=Christopher Andersen | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/topics/Christopher+Andersen | location=New York | work=Daily News | access-date=2010-02-14 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090925024555/http://www.nydailynews.com/topics/Christopher+Andersen | archive-date=2009-09-25 |url-status = dead| df= }}</ref> ''Life'', and ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''.\n\nWhile his early nonfiction books veered from psychology (''The Name Game'') to [[true crime]] (''The Serpent's Tooth'') to art collecting (''The Best of Everything'', with former [[Sotheby's]] chairman John Marion), he is best known for his controversial [[biographies]].  Between 1991 and 2011, he published 14 ''New York Times'' [[bestselling]] biographies. Two of these--''The Day Diana Died'' and ''The Day John Died''\u2014went to No.1.  Andersen's second book about the relationship of President [[John F. Kennedy]] and First Lady [[Jacqueline Kennedy]], ''These Few Precious Days:  The Final Year of Jack with Jackie, '' was published to coincide with the 50th anniversary of JFK's assassination and also became a Top 10 \"New York Times\" bestseller, followed by ''The Good Son: JFK Jr. and the Mother He Loved'' in 2014.  In 2016, ''Game of Crowns'' was published to mark [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]]'s 90th birthday, becoming Andersen's 18th ''Times'' best seller.\n\nSeven of Andersen's titles have also been selected for the ''[[Readers Digest]]'' Today's Best Nonfiction Books of the Year series. In November 2008, NBC's [[Brian Williams]] presented Andersen with a Joan's Legacy Award for excellence in journalism regarding lung cancer, along with ''Ladies Home Journal'', which excerpted the portion of his book ''Somewhere in Heaven: The Remarkable Love Story of Dana and Christopher Reeve'' describing Dana Reeve's battle with lung cancer.  ''Madonna Unauthorized'' (1991) and ''The Day John Died'' (2000) were made into television films.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0026114/ IMDb]</ref>\n\nAndersen has made frequent appearances on TV programs such as the ''[[Today (NBC program)|Today Show]]'', ''[[Good Morning America]]'',   ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'', ''[[Larry King Live]]'',  ''[[The CBS Early Show]]'',  ''[[Dateline]]'', ''[[Extra (U.S. TV program)|Extra]]'', ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]'',  ''[[NBC Nightly News]]'', ''[[ABC World News]]'', ''[[48 Hours (TV series)|48 Hours]]'', ''[[Inside Edition]]'', ''[[Anderson Cooper 360]]'' and ''[[Hardball with Chris Matthews|Hardball]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Obama complained, \"Jesus I wish they'd stop grabbing...\"  | date=22 September 2009 | work=[[The Huffington Post]]| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/09/22/obama-said-jesus-i-wish-t_n_294653.html | first=Rachel | last=Weiner}}</ref>\n\nMarried since 1972 to former international banker Valerie Hess, Andersen resides in [[Connecticut]].  They have two daughters \u2014 former [[Bloomberg News]] [[White House]] correspondent and bestselling author (''The Residence'', ''First Women'') Katharine Andersen Brower (born 1980) and artist Kelly Andersen (born 1990). In April 2016, Andersen's ''Game of Crowns'' and Brower's ''First Women'' were published within days of each other.  At one point, father and daughter occupied five positions on the ''Times'' hardcover, ebook, and combined ebook and hardcover lists.\n\n==Reviews==\n\nAssaying several Kennedy biographies, Larissa MacFarguhar wrote in the ''New York Times'' that Andersen's ''Jack and Jackie'' was \"the most worth reading\" and \"comes closest to making Jackie sparkle.\" Of the sequel, ''Jackie After Jack: Portrait of The Lady,'' ''USA Today'' said \"readers will be spellbound\" while ''Newsweek'' called the book \"poignant\" and \"intimate.\" ''The Day Diana Died'' was also a critical as well as commercial success, with ''Time'' describing the book as \"swift and astounding reading,\" ''People'' calling it \"riveting,\" the ''Washington Post'' citing its \"breathless new details about the last hours of Diana's life\" and the ''Chicago Sun-Times'' deeming the book \"a fabulous, addictive read.\" In his review of ''George and Laura:  Portrait of an American Marriage'', ''Newsweek'''s critic wrote that \"Andersen's insights can be as sharp as his details,\" while in its story on ''The Day John Died'' the Associated Press called Andersen \"the master of the detail-packed tearjerker.\" \nAndersen wrote ''Mick: The Wild Life and Mad Genius of Jagger'' to mark the 50th anniversary of the [[Rolling Stones (band)|Rolling Stones]] in July 2012.  The book quickly became Andersen's 15th ''New York Times'' bestseller. In a review in ''The Guardian'', Dorian Lynskey noted: \"A book about a singer that pays no attention to his songs is simply an anthology of gossip, albeit juicy, unusually well-researched gossip.\".<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/aug/17/mick-jagger-biography-andersen-review Lynskey, Dorian. \"Mick: The Wild Life and Mad Genius of Jagger by Christopher Andersen \u2013 review\", ''The Guardian'', August 17, 2012]</ref>  However, the ''Daily Beast'' called ''Mick'' \"brilliant\" and ''Entertainment Weekly'' described it as \"jam-packed with juiciness.\"\n\nIn a lengthy 1999 ''Salon'' review, Jake Tapper wrote of ''Bill and Hillary: The Marriage'': \"Andersen dishes like a catty high school girl holding forth in the lunchroom.\"  But Tapper also stated that the book's \"depiction of the Clintons' lopsided quid-pro-quo relationship meshes perfectly with the glimmers of insight the Clintons themselves have offered us,\"  concluding that ''Bill and Hillary'' is \"a guilty pleasure\" and that in the end \"the Clintons are getting the book they deserve.\".<ref>[http://www.salon.com/1999/08/26/clintons/ Tapper, Jake. \"The Clinton marriage\", ''Salon'', August 26, 1999]</ref> Similarly, in its review of Andersen's bestselling Streisand biography, ''Barbra:  The Way She Is'', the ''New York Times'' noted that Andersen \"has a knack for ferreting memorable anecdotes of the 'no wire hangers' variety\" while ''USA Today'' claimed the book \"hits all the high notes\" in Streisand's life story.  Terry Hartle of the ''Christian Science Monitor'' wrote that Andersen's ''These Few Precious Days:  The Last Year of Jack with Jackie'' was \"fascinating and insightful\" and ''Kirkus Reviews'' determined that ''The Good Son''was \"sensitive and astute, intimate\" with \"the power to mesmerize.\" ''Vanity Fair'' called Andersen's 2016 book ''Game of Crowns'' \"catnip for royal watchers.\"\n\n==Works==\n*''The Name Game'' (1977)\n*''Father'' (1983)\n*''The Serpent's Tooth'' (1986)\n*''Young Kate: Katharine Hepburn and the Making of an American Legend'' (1988)\n*''The Best of Everything'' (with John Marion) (1989)\n*''Citizen Jane'' (1990)\n*''Madonna: Unauthorized'' (1991)\n*''Jagger: Unauthorized'' (1993)\n*''Michael Jackson: Unauthorized'' (1994)\n*''Jack and Jackie: Portrait of an American Marriage'' (1996)\n*''An Affair to Remember'' (1997)\n*''Jackie After Jack: Portrait of the Lady'' (1998)\n*''The Day Diana Died'' (1998)\n*''Bill and Hillary: The Marriage'' (1999)\n*''The Day John Died'' (2000)\n*''Diana's Boys: William and Harry and the Mother They Loved'' (2001)\n*''George and Laura: Portrait of an American Marriage'' (2002)\n*''Sweet Caroline: Last Child of Camelot'' (2003)\n*''American Evita: Hillary Clinton's Path to Power'' (2004)\n*''Barbra: The Way She Is'' (2006)\n*''After Diana: William, Harry, Charles, and the Royal House of Windsor'' (2007)\n*''Somewhere in Heaven: The Remarkable Love Story of Dana and Christopher Reeve'' (2008)\n*''Barack and Michelle|Barack and Michelle: Portrait of an American Marriage'' (2009) <ref>http://www.harpercollins.com/author/microsite/?authorid=205 Harpercollins.com</ref>\n*''William and Kate: A Royal Love Story'' (2010)\n*''These Few Precious Days: The Final Year of Jack with Jackie'' (2013)\n*''Game of Crowns: Elizabeth, Camilla, Kate, and the Throne'' (2016)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0026114}}\n*[http://www.bookreporter.com/authors/au-andersen-christopher.asp \"Christopher Andersen\", ''Bookreporter'']\n*[http://coaches.aol.com/kids-and-family/feature/_a/christopher-anderson-after-diana/20070627170209990001 'After Diana' Q&A With Christopher Andersen, CAROLINE HOWARD]\n* {{C-SPAN|Christopher Andersen}}\n\n<!--Associated Press, Aug. 11, 1998, July 20, 1999, July 22, 1999, July 11, 2000, July 28, 2000, Aug. 24, 2001, June 21, 2002, Aug. 31, 2002,Jan. 11, 2003, Nov. 2, 2003; \nbookreporter.com; \n''The Boston Globe'', July 8, 1993; August 10, 1996, Aug. 4, 1999, Nov. 22, 2003; \n''Chicago Sun-Times'', June 24, 1996, June 16, 2005; \n''Contemporary Authors'' vols. 14,31,127; \n''Cosmopolitan'', March 1998; \n''Detroit Free Press'', Nov. 16, 2003; \n''Ladies Home Journal'', August 2000, August 2008;\n''New York Magazine'', Feb. 16, 1998;\n''The New York Times'',  Sept. 13, 1982, Aug. 7, 1988,  June 10, 1990, Oct. 18, 1991, July 14, 1996, Mar. 1, 1998, Aug. 14, 1998, Sept. 13, 1998, Oct. 4, 1998, Aug. 22, 1999, Sept. 16, 2001, Sept.23, 2001, Nov. 9, 2003, July 25, 2004, April 16, 2006, July 27, 2008;\n''Newsweek'', May 5, 1997, Feb. 23, 1998;\n''Parade'', Jan. 31, 1988;\n''People'', Nov. 25, 2002, June 18, 2007; \n''Redbook'', September 1, 2001;\n''Time'',  August 19, 1996, April 21, 1997,;\n''USA Today,'' July 7, 2008;\n''US News & World Report'', May 19, 1997; \n''Vanity Fair'', Sept. 2003;\n''Washington Post'',  Aug.7, 1988, Aug. 13, 1998, Aug. 21, 2001-->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andersen, Christopher}}\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American biographers]]\n[[Category:Male biographers]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Celebrity biographers]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the American basketball player|Chris Andersen|people of a similar name|Christopher Anderson (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|name=Christopher Andersen\n|birth_name=Christopher Peter Andersen\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1949|5|26}}\n|birth_place=[[United States]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|occupation=[[Journalist]], [[author]]\n|language=[[English language|English]]\n|genre=[[Journalism]], [[biography]]\n}}\n\n'''Christopher Peter Andersen''' (born May 26, 1949) is an [[United States|American]] [[journalist]] and the author of 34 books, including many bestsellers.\n\n==Life==\nA graduate of the [[University of California at Berkeley]], Andersen joined the staff of ''[[Time Magazine]]'' as a contributing editor in 1969.<ref>{{cite news | title=Search Results for Christopher Andersen | url=http://search.time.com/results.html?N=0&Nty=1&Ntt=Christopher+Andersen&x=17&y=18&p=0&cmd=tags&srchCat=Full+Archive | work=Time | date=June 6, 2007 | access-date=February 14, 2010 | archive-url=https://archive.is/20120718134611/http://search.time.com/results.html?N=0&Nty=1&Ntt=Christopher+Andersen&x=17&y=18&p=0&cmd=tags&srchCat=Full+Archive | archive-date=July 18, 2012 |url-status = dead| df=mdy-all }}</ref>  From 1974 to 1986 Andersen was senior editor of Time Incorporated's ''[[People Magazine]]''.<ref>[http://search.people.com/TIISearch/people/search/search.html?search=Christopher+Andersen&bu=&searchSubmit.x=19&searchSubmit.y=17 People.com] {{dead link|date=September 2018}}</ref>  He has also written for a wide range of  publications, including ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''The New York Daily News'',<ref>{{cite news | title=Christopher Andersen | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/topics/Christopher+Andersen | location=New York | work=Daily News | access-date=2010-02-14 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090925024555/http://www.nydailynews.com/topics/Christopher+Andersen | archive-date=2009-09-25 |url-status = dead| df= }}</ref> ''Life'', and ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''.\n\nWhile his early nonfiction books veered from psychology (''The Name Game'') to [[true crime]] (''The Serpent's Tooth'') to art collecting (''The Best of Everything'', with former [[Sotheby's]] chairman John Marion), he is best known for his controversial [[biographies]].  Between 1991 and 2011, he published 14 ''New York Times'' [[bestselling]] biographies. Two of these--''The Day Diana Died'' and ''The Day John Died''\u2014went to No.1.  Andersen's second book about the relationship of President [[John F. Kennedy]] and First Lady [[Jacqueline Kennedy]], ''These Few Precious Days:  The Final Year of Jack with Jackie, '' was published to coincide with the 50th anniversary of JFK's assassination and also became a Top 10 \"New York Times\" bestseller, followed by ''The Good Son: JFK Jr. and the Mother He Loved'' in 2014.  In 2016, ''Game of Crowns'' was published to mark [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]]'s 90th birthday, becoming Andersen's 18th ''Times'' best seller.\n\nSeven of Andersen's titles have also been selected for the ''[[Readers Digest]]'' Today's Best Nonfiction Books of the Year series. In November 2008, NBC's [[Brian Williams]] presented Andersen with a Joan's Legacy Award for excellence in journalism regarding lung cancer, along with ''Ladies Home Journal'', which excerpted the portion of his book ''Somewhere in Heaven: The Remarkable Love Story of Dana and Christopher Reeve'' describing Dana Reeve's battle with lung cancer.  ''Madonna Unauthorized'' (1991) and ''The Day John Died'' (2000) were made into television films.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0026114/ IMDb]</ref>\n\nAndersen has made frequent appearances on TV programs such as the ''[[Today (NBC program)|Today Show]]'', ''[[Good Morning America]]'',   ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'', ''[[Larry King Live]]'',  ''[[The CBS Early Show]]'',  ''[[Dateline]]'', ''[[Extra (U.S. TV program)|Extra]]'', ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]'',  ''[[NBC Nightly News]]'', ''[[ABC World News]]'', ''[[48 Hours (TV series)|48 Hours]]'', ''[[Inside Edition]]'', ''[[Anderson Cooper 360]]'' and ''[[Hardball with Chris Matthews|Hardball]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Obama complained, \"Jesus I wish they'd stop grabbing...\"  | date=22 September 2009 | work=[[The Huffington Post]]| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/09/22/obama-said-jesus-i-wish-t_n_294653.html | first=Rachel | last=Weiner}}</ref>\n\nMarried since 1972 to former international banker Valerie Hess, Andersen resides in [[Connecticut]].  They have two daughters \u2014 former [[Bloomberg News]] [[White House]] correspondent and bestselling author (''The Residence'', ''First Women'') Katharine Andersen Brower (born 1980) and artist Kelly Andersen (born 1990). In April 2016, Andersen's ''Game of Crowns'' and Brower's ''First Women'' were published within days of each other.  At one point, father and daughter occupied five positions on the ''Times'' hardcover, ebook, and combined ebook and hardcover lists.\n\n==Reviews==\n\nAssaying several Kennedy biographies, Larissa MacFarguhar wrote in the ''New York Times'' that Andersen's ''Jack and Jackie'' was \"the most worth reading\" and \"comes closest to making Jackie sparkle.\" Of the sequel, ''Jackie After Jack: Portrait of The Lady,'' ''USA Today'' said \"readers will be spellbound\" while ''Newsweek'' called the book \"poignant\" and \"intimate.\" ''The Day Diana Died'' was also a critical as well as commercial success, with ''Time'' describing the book as \"swift and astounding reading,\" ''People'' calling it \"riveting,\" the ''Washington Post'' citing its \"breathless new details about the last hours of Diana's life\" and the ''Chicago Sun-Times'' deeming the book \"a fabulous, addictive read.\" In his review of ''George and Laura:  Portrait of an American Marriage'', ''Newsweek'''s critic wrote that \"Andersen's insights can be as sharp as his details,\" while in its story on ''The Day John Died'' the Associated Press called Andersen \"the master of the detail-packed tearjerker.\" \nAndersen wrote ''Mick: The Wild Life and Mad Genius of Jagger'' to mark the 50th anniversary of the [[Rolling Stones (band)|Rolling Stones]] in July 2012.  The book quickly became Andersen's 15th ''New York Times'' bestseller. In a review in ''The Guardian'', Dorian Lynskey noted: \"A book about a singer that pays no attention to his songs is simply an anthology of gossip, albeit juicy, unusually well-researched gossip.\".<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/aug/17/mick-jagger-biography-andersen-review Lynskey, Dorian. \"Mick: The Wild Life and Mad Genius of Jagger by Christopher Andersen \u2013 review\", ''The Guardian'', August 17, 2012]</ref>  However, the ''Daily Beast'' called ''Mick'' \"brilliant\" and ''Entertainment Weekly'' described it as \"jam-packed with juiciness.\"\n\nIn a lengthy 1999 ''Salon'' review, Jake Tapper wrote of ''Bill and Hillary: The Marriage'': \"Andersen dishes like a catty high school girl holding forth in the lunchroom.\"  But Tapper also stated that the book's \"depiction of the Clintons' lopsided quid-pro-quo relationship meshes perfectly with the glimmers of insight the Clintons themselves have offered us,\"  concluding that ''Bill and Hillary'' is \"a guilty pleasure\" and that in the end \"the Clintons are getting the book they deserve.\".<ref>[http://www.salon.com/1999/08/26/clintons/ Tapper, Jake. \"The Clinton marriage\", ''Salon'', August 26, 1999]</ref> Similarly, in its review of Andersen's bestselling Streisand biography, ''Barbra:  The Way She Is'', the ''New York Times'' noted that Andersen \"has a knack for ferreting memorable anecdotes of the 'no wire hangers' variety\" while ''USA Today'' claimed the book \"hits all the high notes\" in Streisand's life story.  Terry Hartle of the ''Christian Science Monitor'' wrote that Andersen's ''These Few Precious Days:  The Last Year of Jack with Jackie'' was \"fascinating and insightful\" and ''Kirkus Reviews'' determined that ''The Good Son''was \"sensitive and astute, intimate\" with \"the power to mesmerize.\" ''Vanity Fair'' called Andersen's 2016 book ''Game of Crowns'' \"catnip for royal watchers.\"\n\n==Works==\n*''The Name Game'' (1977)\n*''Father'' (1983)\n*''The Serpent's Tooth'' (1986)\n*''Young Kate: Katharine Hepburn and the Making of an American Legend'' (1988)\n*''The Best of Everything'' (with John Marion) (1989)\n*''Citizen Jane'' (1990)\n*''Madonna: Unauthorized'' (1991)\n*''Jagger: Unauthorized'' (1993)\n*''Michael Jackson: Unauthorized'' (1994)\n*''Jack and Jackie: Portrait of an American Marriage'' (1996)\n*''An Affair to Remember'' (1997)\n*''Jackie After Jack: Portrait of the Lady'' (1998)\n*''The Day Diana Died'' (1998)\n*''Bill and Hillary: The Marriage'' (1999)\n*''The Day John Died'' (2000)\n*''Diana's Boys: William and Harry and the Mother They Loved'' (2001)\n*''George and Laura: Portrait of an American Marriage'' (2002)\n*''Sweet Caroline: Last Child of Camelot'' (2003)\n*''American Evita: Hillary Clinton's Path to Power'' (2004)\n*''Barbra: The Way She Is'' (2006)\n*''After Diana: William, Harry, Charles, and the Royal House of Windsor'' (2007)\n*''Somewhere in Heaven: The Remarkable Love Story of Dana and Christopher Reeve'' (2008)\n*''Barack and Michelle|Barack and Michelle: Portrait of an American Marriage'' (2009) <ref>http://www.harpercollins.com/author/microsite/?authorid=205 Harpercollins.com</ref>\n*''William and Kate: A Royal Love Story'' (2010)\n*''These Few Precious Days: The Final Year of Jack with Jackie'' (2013)\n*''Game of Crowns: Elizabeth, Camilla, Kate, and the Throne'' (2016)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0026114}}\n*[http://www.bookreporter.com/authors/au-andersen-christopher.asp \"Christopher Andersen\", ''Bookreporter'']\n*[http://coaches.aol.com/kids-and-family/feature/_a/christopher-anderson-after-diana/20070627170209990001 'After Diana' Q&A With Christopher Andersen, CAROLINE HOWARD]\n* {{C-SPAN|Christopher Andersen}}\n\n<!--Associated Press, Aug. 11, 1998, July 20, 1999, July 22, 1999, July 11, 2000, July 28, 2000, Aug. 24, 2001, June 21, 2002, Aug. 31, 2002,Jan. 11, 2003, Nov. 2, 2003; \nbookreporter.com; \n''The Boston Globe'', July 8, 1993; August 10, 1996, Aug. 4, 1999, Nov. 22, 2003; \n''Chicago Sun-Times'', June 24, 1996, June 16, 2005; \n''Contemporary Authors'' 